Awareness Commands Linux
Date and Time
    • date [OPTION]... [+FORMAT]
    • date [-u|--utc|--universal] [MMDDhhmm[[CC]YY][.ss]]
CPU/ Memory Usage 
    • To check the statistics on the cpu/processor:
        ◦ dmidecode [OPTIONS]
    • To check CPU/memory usage on a Linux system, use the top or free command:
        ◦ free [OPTIONS]
        ◦ top [-b] [-nCOUNT] [-dSECONDS] [-m]
            ▪ Note: Using the top command will ‘take-over’ your terminal
Disk Usage
    • fdisk
        ◦ Partition table manipulator for Linux
    • du
        ◦ Estimate file space usage
    • df
        ◦ Display free disk space
    • quota
        ◦ Display disk usage and limits
    • mount
        ◦ Mount a file system
    • lspci
        ◦ List all PCI devices
    • lsblk
        ◦ List block devices
    • lsusb
        ◦ List all USB devices
Processor Architecture
    • lscpu ← This one is goated
    • uname -a
Machine ID
    • ifconfig - displays the status of the currently active interfaces
        ◦ useful command-line options: -a
    • ip - protocol (IP or IPv6) address on a device
        ◦ useful command-line options: address, neighbor, route, tunnel
    • hostname - display the system's DNS name; display/set its hostname or NIS domain name
        ◦ useful command-line options: -A
    • uname - print certain system information
        ◦ useful command-line options: -a, -r, -v, -m, -i, -o
    • cat /etc/*rel*
Process 
    • ps -elf
Open Ports/Connections
    • netstat [-ral] [-tuwx] [-enWp] <--- Most ‘Nix varieties
    • ss [OPTIONS] [FILTER] <--- too many options to list here
Jobs
    • crontab [ -u user ] [ -i ] {-e | -l | -r }
        ◦ DO NOT JUST USE ‘CRONTAB’. IT ERASES LISTINGS 

Modifying Timestamps
    • touch -r

USE ‘W’ TO SEE CURRENTLY LOGGED IN USERS ON ENTRY AND EXIT. ALERT MC FOR LOGGED IN ROOT USER
